Input Output <code>abcabcbb</code> 3 <code>(abc)</code> <code>bbbb</code> 1 <code>(b)</code> <code>pwwkew</code> 3 <code>(wke)</code> Solution <p>Since we are looking for contiguous section (i.e. substring), use a running window.</p> <p>The idea is to keep adding characters to this running window and thus keep increasing the size of candidate substring as long as the characters encountered are unique.</p> <p>As soon as we hit a duplicate, we need to reset the running window. Say we encounter a character first time at index <code>2</code> and then again at <code>5</code>, then index <code>2</code> is spoiled.</p> <p> abcdecflongest substring = "a"abcdecflongest substring = "ab"abcdecflongest substring = "abc"abcdecflongest substring = "abcd"abcdecflongest substring = "abcde"abcdecffound a previously repeating charabcdecf  reset running windowlongest substring = "dec"abcdecflongest substring = "decf" </p> Implementation <pre><code>int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
if (s == null) return 0;
if (s.length() &lt; 2) return s.length();
Map&lt;Character, Integer&gt; seenAt = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
int maxLength = 0;
for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++) {
char c = s.charAt(i);
if (seenAt.containsKey(c)) {
// found a duplicate character.
int priorIndex = seenAt.get(c);
// reset running window.
seenAt.entrySet().removeIf(entry -&gt; entry.getValue() &lt;= priorIndex);
seenAt.put(c, i);
} else {
// all good. keep appending to candidate substring.
seenAt.put(c, i);
maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, seenAt.size());
}
}
return maxLength;
}
</code></pre>

Input Output [1, 2, 3] [1, 3, 2] [2, 3, 1] [3, 1, 2] [3, 2, 1] [1, 2, 3] [1, 1, 5] [1, 5, 1] [4, 2, 0, 2, 3, 2, 0] [4, 2, 0, 3, 0, 2, 2] <p>Note</p> <p>We are not looking for the closest neighbour in the permutation space. It should be the permutation with least difference.</p> Solution <p>The idea is to "dial up" followed by a "dial down".</p> <ol> <li> <p>We first find the lowest possible number which can be swapped by a number larger than it to it's right. For example: \([...4...9] \implies [...9...4]\).</p> </li> <li> <p>The resulting number has jumped ahead a bit too much. It should be "dialed back". So we need to go go down by sorting the bolded subarray \([...9\textbf{...4}]\).</p> </li> </ol> <p> 4202320Nothing &gt;2 on right4202320Nothing &gt;3 on right4202320"dial up" Found something &gt;24203220"dial down" with swap <p></p> Implementation <pre><code>public boolean nextPermutation(int[] nums) {
if (nums == null || nums.length &lt; 2) {
return false;
}
for (int i = nums.length - 2; i &gt;= 0; i--) {
// Find the smallest number to the right, which is still greater than nums[i].
int candidate = findNext(nums, i + 1, nums.length, nums[i]);
if (candidate &gt;= 0) {
swap(nums, i, candidate);
Arrays.sort(nums, i + 1, nums.length);
return true;
}
}
Arrays.sort(nums);
return false;
}
private int findNext(int[] nums, int start, int end, int threshold) {
int min = start;
for (int i = start; i &lt; end; i++) {
if (nums[i] &gt; threshold &amp;&amp; nums[i] &lt; nums[min]) {
min = i;
}
}
return nums[min] &gt; threshold ? min : -1;
}
private void swap(int[] nums, int i, int j) {
int t = nums[i];
nums[i] = nums[j];
nums[j] = t;
}
